{SECT 0 {PARA 256 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 " Getting Started With Basic Cal
culation" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
313 "Save your current worksheet as number01.mws.  Remember to save fr
equently in case of system shut downs in the middle of a work session!
 In the text mode (click on the cap T button) place your name(s) and d
ate at the top of your worksheet.  At the end of this session you will
 print out and turn in your worksheet." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 245 "We begin by experimenting with some \+
very basic calculations.  The intent is to learn some basic MAPLE synt
ax, while observing some of the neat features of a Computer Algebra Sy
stem (CAS).  We will also review some basic concepts from arithmetic.
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 842 "Perf
orm the following calculations with MAPLE.  As you do these exercises \+
enter notes and comments onto your worksheet in text mode.  In particu
lar, the author of these worksheets sometimes purposefully leaves off \+
certain required MAPLE syntax.  He is either sadistic or he is trying \+
to make a point.  Let's assume the latter for now. The first example i
s in the first problem below.  A CAS requires some syntaxual thing to \+
tell it when you are through giving it instructions on what you want i
t to do and ready for it to do them.  Try the first calculation just a
s indicated, look at the error message and see if you can figure out w
hat syntax is required by MAPLE to tell it that you are ready for it t
o do its thing. (Place the cursor on the execution line indicated by t
he symbol [> and type in your MAPLE instructions, a. k. a. \"input.\")
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 7 "1.  6+
2" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 117 "Another example of \"omi
tted\" required MAPLE syntax is in the next problem.  It's more subtle
 and you may have to ask." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 10 "2.  2(3+5)" 
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 218 "Can you figure out just what M
APLE was doing to come up with the answer it gave for #2?  In other wo
rds \"How did MAPLE interpret the operation  2(3+5)?\"  To answer this
 try some more examples like 2(34), 2(x-6), 2(t). " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 78 "(You can always get a new execution line by clicking on [
> from the toolbar.) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 63 "ALL QUESTIONS/STATEMENTS IN BOLD FACE REQUIRE WRITTEN \+
RESPONSE." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }{TEXT 262 7 "Answer:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "Continue with the following calculations:" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "3.  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(1/5)^2+2" "6#,&*$*&
\"\"\"F&\"\"&!\"\"\"\"#F&F)F&" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 
0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 44 "Note the effect of the next exe
cution line. " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "evalf(%);" }
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 263 15 "What d
id it do?" }{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "4.  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(13-7)/7" "6#*&,&\"#8\"\"\"\"
\"(!\"\"F&F'F(" }{TEXT -1 2 "  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 30 "Again try the evalf() command
." }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "evalf(%);" }}}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "5.  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "((8^2-3^3)*(5-22))/(8-4^2)" "
6#*(,&*$\"\")\"\"#\"\"\"*$\"\"$F*!\"\"F(,&\"\"&F(\"#AF+F(,&F&F(*$\"\"%
F'F+F+" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 30 "Again try the evalf() command." }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 
0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "evalf(%);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "6.  " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(27!)/(10!*17!)" "6#*&-%*factorialG6#\"#F\"\"\"*&-F%6#
\"#5F(-F%6#\"#<F(!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 37 "Note how this compar
es with the next " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "binomia
l(27,10);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 43 "7.  Try the MAPLE command b
inomial(100,50);" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 38 "8.  Compute the corresponding  number " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "100!/(50!*50!) " "6#*&-%*factorialG6#\"$+\"\"\"\"*&-F%6
#\"#]F(-F%6#F,F(!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 2 " ." }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 257 116 "This expression is called the \"binomia
l coefficient\" and sometimes referred to as \"100 choose 50.\"  Do yo
u know why?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 143 "9.  Execute the following command sequence and record any rele
vant observations about what the commands do, automatic features of MA
PLE, etc.  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "1+2/3;" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "evalf(%);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 
"> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 12 "1/2+1/3+1/4;" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "evalf(%);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 8 
